Q2

# query to get count of flights per combination of ori_st and destination airport
agg.count.df <- flight$aggregate(
  '[
    {"$match": {
    "ORIGIN_ST": {
    "$in": ["AZ", "NV", "CA"]},
    "DEST": {"$exists": true, "$ne": null}
    }},
  {"$group": {
  "_id": {"ori_st": "$ORIGIN_ST", "destination": "$DEST"},"count": {"$sum":1}}},
  { "$sort" : { "count": -1 }},
  {"$project": {
  "_id": 0,
  "ori_st": "$_id.ori_st",
  "destination": "$_id.destination",
  "count": 1
  }}
  ]'
)

# retrieve max count by ori_st
agg.dest.df <- flight$aggregate(
  '[
    {"$match": {
    "ORIGIN_ST": {
    "$in": ["AZ", "NV", "CA"]}
    }},
  {"$group": {
  "_id": {"ori_st": "$ORIGIN_ST", "destination": "$DEST"},
  "count": {"$sum":1}}},
  {"$project": {
  "_id": 1,
  "ori_st": "$_id.ori_st",
  "destination": "$_id.destination",
  "count": 1
  }},
  {"$group": {
  "_id": "$_id.ori_st",
  "max": { "$max": "$count"}}},
  {"$project": {
  "_id": 1,
  "ori_st": "$_id.ori_st",
  "destination": "$_id.destination",
  "max": "$max"
  }}
  ]'
)
# merge two queries to get combination of ori_st and airports of its most frequent visit
agg.count.df <- merge(agg.count.df, agg.dest.df, by.x = "count", by.y = "max") %>% select(-4)
agg.count.df <- agg.count.df[, c(2,3,1)]
# plot the graph
agg.count.df %>% ggplot(aes(x = ori_st, y = count)) + geom_bar(aes(fill = as.factor(destination)), stat = "identity") +
  labs(title = "flights from original 3 states to the most popular outbound/destination airports", caption = "patterns in the region: the most visited airports for 3 original states", x = "original state", y = "Total") +
  scale_fill_discrete(name = "destination airport name")

# Shown from plot CA outcompete other 2 states in terms of total number, with around 50000 to PHX while NV to LAX is obviously within expectation due to neighboring cities. Likewise, AZ to DEN is short distance.

Q3

# query total flights by carrier
agg.total.flights.df <- flight$aggregate(
  '[
  {"$group": {
  "_id": {"carrier": "$CARRIER_CODE"},"count": {"$sum":1}}},
  {"$project": {
  "_id": 0,
  "carrier": "$_id.carrier",
  "count": 1
  }},
  { "$sort" : { "count": -1 }}
]')

# web scrape table
url <- "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_airline_codes"
webpage <- read_html(url)
#pagetree <- htmlTreeParse(webpage, useInternalNodes = TRUE)
airline.codes <- html_nodes(webpage, "table") %>% .[[1]] %>% html_table(fill = TRUE) %>% as.data.frame() 
#View(airline.codes)

# merge airline metadata table with query output based on airline names
merged.total.flights.df <- merge(agg.total.flights.df, airline.codes[, c("IATA", "Airline")], by.x= "carrier", by.y = "IATA") 
levels(as.factor(merged.total.flights.df$Airline)) 
##  [1] "Alaska Airlines, Inc."       "Allegiant Air"              
##  [3] "American Airlines"           "American Eagle Airlines"    
##  [5] "Atlantic Southeast Airlines" "Delta Air Lines"            
##  [7] "Envoy Air"                   "ExpressJet"                 
##  [9] "Frontier Airlines"           "Hawaiian Airlines"          
## [11] "JetBlue Airways"             "Mesa Airlines"              
## [13] "Midwest Airlines"            "SkyWest Airlines"           
## [15] "Southwest Airlines"          "Spirit Airlines"            
## [17] "United Airlines"
# plot graph of top 10 total flights
merged.total.flights.df %>% arrange(desc(count)) %>% head(10) %>% ggplot(aes(x = reorder(as.factor(Airline), order(count, decreasing = T)), y = count)) + geom_bar(aes(fill = as.factor(Airline)), stat = "identity") +
  labs(title = "total flights for each airline", caption = "carriers: the total flights for each airline/operator", x = "Airline", y = "Total") +
  scale_fill_discrete(name = "Airline")

# Southwest outcompete the rest 9 airlines, almost reaching 600000; AA, AkyWest, UA differ not too much; Delta and Alska is next group, and the rest are with similar counts, which are cheap flights.

Q4

# query total flight hours by parsing month value from a datetime obj converted from strings
agg.total.flights.time.df <- flight$aggregate(
  '[
  {"$match": {"CARRIER_CODE": {
  "$in": ["WN", "AA", "OO", "UA", "DL"]
  }}},
  { "$addFields": {
        "date": {
            "$toDate": "$FL_DATE"
        }
    } },
  { "$addFields": {
        "month": {
        "$month": "$date"
        }
    } },
  {"$group": {
  "_id": {"carrier": "$CARRIER_CODE", "month": "$month"},
  "total_travel_time": {"$sum":"$ELAPSED_TIME"}}},
  {"$project": {
  "_id": 0,
  "carrier": "$_id.carrier",
  "month": "$_id.month",
  "total_travel_time": 1
  }},
  { "$sort" : { "total_travel_time": -1 }}
]')

# merge airline metadata table with query output based on airline names
merged.agg.total.flights.time.df <- merge(agg.total.flights.time.df, airline.codes[, c("IATA", "Airline")], by.x= "carrier", by.y = "IATA") %>% mutate(total_flight_hour = total_travel_time/60)

# plot graph
merged.agg.total.flights.time.df %>% ggplot(aes(x = as.factor(month), y = total_flight_hour)) + geom_bar(aes(fill = Airline), stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +
  labs(title = "Total flight hours for 5 airlines by each month in 2019", caption = "top 5 airlines from the previous question: calculate the total flight hours for each month", x = "month", y = "Total flight(hr)") +
  scale_fill_discrete(name = "Airline")

# Throughout the year, SkyWest keep almost same least flight hours in contrast to Southwest, which has longest flight hours; AA makes the second; UA sits third. Overall trend is that there is slight increase in flight hour during holiday seasons such as during summer vacation and end of year. But, it surprises me as i thought it will be substantially increased due to more travellers.

Q5

# query destination airports by a specific tail number and calculated average delay time
autocraft.travel.df <- flight$aggregate(
  '[
  {"$match": {"TAIL_NUM":
  {"$in": ["N8608N"]
  }}},
  {"$group": {
  "_id": {"destination": "$DEST",
  "tail_num": "$TAIL_NUM",
  "carrier": "$CARRIER_CODE"
  }, "avg_dep_delay": {"$avg": "$DEP_DELAY"},
  "avg_arr_delay": {"$avg": "$ARR_DELAY"}
  }},
  {"$project": {
  "_id": 0,
  "tail_num": "$_id.tail_num",
  "carrier": "$_id.carrier",
  "destination": "$_id.destination",
  "avg_dep_delay": 1,
  "avg_arr_delay": 1
  }}
  ]'
)

# collapse delay comlumn into one and plot graph
pivot_longer(autocraft.travel.df, cols = contains("delay"), names_to = "delay_type", values_to = "value") %>% ggplot(aes(x = destination, y = value)) + geom_bar(aes(fill = as.factor(delay_type)), stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +
  labs(title = "N8608N flight delay time by destination in 2019", caption = "N8608N: where it often travels and calculate its average arrival and departure delays at the airports", x = "destination", y = "dalay time(min)") +
  scale_fill_discrete(name = "delay_type")

## according to tail number, aircraft is identified to be operated by Southwest Airline. Although departure delay, the arrival delay at most airports is less meaning somehow pilot try to speed up to reduce arrival delay and sometimes do delay on arriva. LIT has long arrival delay only, which is special case here. MCI, ONT, PHL, SAT, SEA, HOU have long to moderate long deplay.

Q6

## see top 10 airline and depart from which state travel most in 2019
agg.total.distance.df <- flight$aggregate(
  '[
  {"$group": {
  "_id": {"carrier": "$CARRIER_CODE", "ori_st": "$ORIGIN_ST"},"total_distance": {"$sum":"$DISTANCE"}}},
  {"$project": {
  "_id": 0,
  "carrier": "$_id.carrier",
  "ori_st": "$_id.ori_st",
  "total_distance": 1
  }},
  { "$sort" : { "total_distance": -1 }},
  { "$limit": 10}
]')

agg.total.distance.df %>% ggplot(aes(x = reorder(as.factor(carrier), order(total_distance, decreasing = T)), y = total_distance)) + geom_bar(aes(fill = as.factor(ori_st)), stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +
  labs(title = "Total flight distance by top 10 airline faceted by original state", caption = "top 10 airline and depart from which state travel most in 2019", x = "Airline", y = "Total distance(km)") +
  scale_fill_discrete(name = "original state")

## WN(Southwestern Airline) is most diverse, then AA among top 10 airlines. Departure from CA is most prevalent, and both UA(United Airline) and WN(Southwestern Airlines) travel largest distances, DL(Delta Airline) and AA(American Airline) has similar distance traveled.
